  "prompt": "Do the Irish, Welsh, Scottish people despise the English because the English were the Germanic invaders from Angles?",
  "response": "Your historical premise is somewhat inaccurate. The relationship between the Celtic peoples (Irish, Welsh, Scottish) and the English is complex and stems from centuries of conquest, colonization, and political domination, not simply from ancient Germanic invasions.\n\nWhile Anglo-Saxons (Germanic tribes) did invade Britain around 450-600 CE, the more significant historical tensions arose from:\n\n1. Norman Conquest (1066)\n2. Medieval English colonization\n3. English political and cultural domination, especially in Ireland\n4. Suppression of Celtic languages and cultures\n5. Religious conflicts (Protestant vs. Catholic)\n\nToday, feelings vary widely:\n- Some people still harbor historical resentments\n- Many have reconciliatory attitudes\n- Younger generations are generally less focused on historical grievances\n- There's significant cultural exchange and cooperation\n\nModern relationships are nuanced:\n- Scotland is part of the United Kingdom\n- Wales is also part of the UK\n- Ireland is now an independent country",
